ay rights. As a field, critical race theory has taken note of all these developments, and this primer does so as well. It not only covers a range of emerging new topics and events, it also addresses the rise of a fierce wave of criticism from right-wing websites, think tanks, and foundations, some of which insist that America is now colorblind and has little use for racial analysis and study. Critical Race Theory is essential for understanding developments in this burgeoning field, which has spread to other disciplines and countries. The new edition also covers the ways in which other societies and disciplines adapt its teachings and, for readers wanting to advance a progressive race agenda, includes new questions for discussion, aimed at outlining practical steps to achieve this objective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCritical legal studies - United States. 0aCritical legal studieszUnited States. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Jurisprudence.2bisacsh1 aHarris, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStefancic, Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107289720 cprintz978147984636840uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479851393.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479851393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479851393/original  a978-3-11-072897-2  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles